        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>While no measurements are available for neutron star X-ray binaries at mm frequencies besides our Cycle 2 observations, the expectation is that the mm emission is due to synchrotron emission from a jet (based on observations at radio wavelengths). Therefore, we do not expect line emission and request continuum observations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Extended emission from a compact jet in X-ray binaries at radio wavelengths has only been detected for the BH XRB Cyg X-1 (Stirling et al. 2001) and GRS 1915+105 (Dhawan et al. 2000) with VLBA at 8 GHz and its size estimated to be &lt; 15 mas. Therefore, we do not expect to resolve the jet emission with any of the Cycle 3 configurations and therefore do not impose any requirement for a given configuration.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We measure a flux of 0.33 mJy in our Cycle 2 observations of a persistent neutron star X-ray binary in the soft state. Therefore, allowing for a factor of 2 variation between sources and to ensure a jet detection in the soft state, should there be any, we request a rms of 0.03 mJy. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To summarise the constraints given already in the control and performance parameters, we ask for 3 observations of a neutron star X-ray transient. The first visit should occur a few days after triggering while the subsequent visits should be spaced by about 2 weeks each. Each visit consists of a measurement in band 3 and one in band 7. However, should the ALMA scheduling constraints permit only one measurement we give clear priority to the band 7 science goal. We also note that while 3 visits maximize the chances of detecting a change in the jet break, should one visit not be possible because of weather or scheduling constraints, 2 visits would already set significant constraints on jet variability. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_TIME_CONSTRAINT</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
